Koninkrijk","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Aske, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1200–":"about 1200–Deceased","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1248–Male":"1248–Deceased","1288–Male":"1288–Deceased","1290–Male":"1290–Deceased","1200–Female":"1200–Deceased","<1248>":"1248","1248":"1248","Abt 1200":"about 1200","about 1290":"about 1290","1288":"1288","1200":"1200","before 1240":"before 1240","about 1288":"about 1288","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Aske, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"England","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Middle English <i>Engelond</i> ‘England’. It was probably a formal alternative to   English  , which is also well evidenced as a surname in England. These names may have been acquired by English landowners who moved in Norman social circles or who lived in a neighbouring country (Scotland, Wales, or Ireland), or by English merchants who traded abroad.","Norwegian: habitational name from any of various farmsteads so named, from Old Norse <i>eng</i> ‘meadow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","Swedish: ornamental name with the same meaning as 2."],"variants":[{"name":"English","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Welsh: ethnic name from Middle English <i>English</i>, <i>Inglish</i>, <i>Inglis</i> ‘English’ (Old English <i>Englisc</i>), sometimes alternating with Anglo-Norman French <i>Engleis</i>, <i>Engles</i>, <i>Anglais</i>, <i>Angles</i> (Old French <i>Englois</i>). Compare   Inglis   and   England  . Among the aristocracy and upper gentry it marked out a man of English ancestry from one of Norman or continental origin. In counties bordering England with Scotland and Wales the name distinguished an Englishman from a Scot or a native Welshman on both sides of the border. The name may also have been acquired by English merchants who traded abroad or who lived and worked in a ‘French’ borough in England (one exclusively administered by Normans).","Irish: in Ireland, this name was used to denote an Englishman, often being adopted for Irish <b>Aingléis</b> ‘Englishman’ or through mistranslation for <b>Mac an Ghallóglaigh</b>, see   Gallogly   and   Golightly  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret of England was born about 1200, in England, United Kingdom. She married Roger de Aske. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1200–":"umbes 1200–Surnud","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1200–Female":"1200–Surnud","<1248>":"1248","1248":"1248","Abt 1200":"umbes 1200","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1288":"1288","1200":"1200","before 1240":"enne 1240","about 1288":"umbes 1288","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aske, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1200–":"noin 1200–Kuollut","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1248–Male":"1248–Kuollut","1288–Male":"1288–Kuollut","1290–Male":"1290–Kuollut","1200–Female":"1200–Kuollut","<1248>":"1248","1248":"1248","Abt 1200":"noin 1200","about 1290":"noin 1290","1288":"1288","1200":"1200","before 1240":"ennen vuotta 1240","about 1288":"noin 1288","1240":"1240","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, England","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Aske, Yorkshire, England":"Aske, Easby, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1200–":"environ 1200–Décédée","1200–1280":"1200–1280","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1248–Male":"1248–Décédé","1288–Male":"1288–Décédé","1290–Male":"1290–Décédé","1200–Female":"1200–Décédée","<1248>":"1248","1248":"1248","Abt 1200":"environ 1200","about 1290":"environ 1290","1288":"1288","120